By default, Mockito mock objects try to return &quot;nice&quot; values - for example, if return type is a List, returns an empty List. Only when there is no good options, it returns `null`. 

But with `Future` or Guava&#39;s `ListenableFuture` return types, `null` is not really a &quot;nice&quot; return value. I would say a better default return value should be a immediate future that returns `null` when resolved. Is there a way to change the default return values without having to mock each individual methods?

**Addendum**

Turns out mockito offers a way to do a default global configuration: https://static.javadoc.io/org.mockito/mockito-core/2.2.7/org/mockito/configuration/IMockitoConfiguration.html

So, I can do the following:

    public class MockitoConfiguration extends DefaultMockitoConfiguration {
      @Override
      public Answer&lt;Object&gt; getDefaultAnswer() {
        return new ReturnsEmptyValues() {
          @Override
          public Object answer(InvocationOnMock invocation) {
            Class&lt;?&gt; type = invocation.getMethod().getReturnType();
            if (ListenableFuture.class.isAssignableFrom(type)) {
              return Futures.immediateFuture(null);
            }
            return super.answer(invocation);
          }
        };
      }
    }

It returns an immediate future with null as the value. It could have been better if I can recursively return a good default for the future value too but with type erasure, I think that&#39;s not a straightforward thing to do.

